  {
    "question": "What is the historical background of MSFEA?",
    "answer": "The Maroun Semaan Faculty of Engineering and Architecture (MSFEA) at AUB, named in 2017 after alumnus and philanthropist Maroun Semaan, traces its engineering education roots back to 1913, awarding its first civil engineering degree in 1944. The School of Engineering was founded in 1951, later expanding to include new undergraduate, master’s, and PhD programs across multiple disciplines, as well as initiatives like the Career Development Center (2002). Today, MSFEA is AUB’s second-largest faculty, with over 2,300 undergraduates, 350 master’s students, nearly 100 PhD students, and 175+ faculty. Since 2017, under Dean Alan Shihadeh, the faculty has embraced innovation, pedagogy reform, and socially responsible research, symbolized by the FEA Graduate’s Oath. The faculty’s growth has been supported by major alumni and donor contributions, funding key facilities like the Bechtel Engineering Building, Ray R. Irani Oxy Engineering Complex, and upcoming Munib & Angela Masri Building, as well as endowed departments, chairs, research hubs, scholarships, and fellowships that strengthen its academic and research mission.",
    "section": "General Knowledge"
  },
  {
    "question": "Who is the dean of MSFEA?",
    "answer": "Alan Shihadeh is Professor and Dean of the Maroun Semaan Faculty of Engineering and Architecture at the American University of Beirut (AUB). He leads initiatives to digitize learning, re-integrate human-centered design in STEM, expand educational access, build regional partnerships for sustainable enterprise, and leverage the Arab region’s context for innovative research toward a more equitable world. Shihadeh is the founding director of AUB’s Aerosol Research Laboratory and a leading researcher on particle pollutants, with 130+ peer-reviewed publications. His work has shaped Lebanon’s tobacco control law, led to bans on leaded fuel and certain diesel vehicles, and influenced international standards for waterpipe tobacco smoke testing. He directs projects for the Virginia Commonwealth Center for the Study of Tobacco Products (an FDA Center of Regulatory Science) and has developed research technologies used worldwide. Recognized as a Clarivate Highly Cited Researcher and winner of the APA Prize for Interdisciplinary Team Research, Shihadeh’s work has been funded by NIH, FDA, and Canada’s IDRC. He earned his BS at the University of Texas at Austin, a PhD in mechanical engineering from MIT (1998), taught as a Fulbright fellow at Birzeit University, and has been with AUB since 2000, serving as dean since 2017.",
